We love a bit of fruit on meat action! Everyone loves a bit of apple sauce on their
pork, but if you've never had orange glazed pork, now's your chance. We adore the way
it works with fluffy couscous and mediterranean veggies.

Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Zest the @orange{1} and squeeze out the juice
into a large #bowl{} (put the zest in the bowl too), add in the @soy sauce{3%tbsp}
and the @sugar{1%tsp} and mix it together. Put the @pork medallions{4} in the bowl,
give everything a little stir until your pork is covered in the mixture. Leave to
the side to marinate while you prepare everything else.

Cut the @red onion{1} in half through the root, peel and slice thinly into half moon
shapes. Remove the cores from the @red pepper{1} and @green pepper{1} and chop into
roughly 2cm pieces. Chop the @courgette{1} into 2cm pieces. Roughly chop the
@flat leaf parsley{1/2%bunch}.

Put your peppers and courgette on a #baking tray{} with a glug of @oil{a glug},
sprinkle over a good pinch of @salt{pinch} and a good grind of @pepper{a good
grind}. Give the tray a good shake and pop in your oven for ~{20-25%minutes} until
cooked and slightly crispy.

Meanwhile, put your onion in a #saucepan{} on low heat with a drizzle of
@oil{a drizzle} and cook for ~{10%minutes} until soft. Add the
@balsamic vinegar{1%tbsp} and cook for another ~{10%minutes} on low heat. When your
onion is soft and caramelised, put a lid on the pan, take it off the heat and leave
to the side until everything else is ready.

Put a #pot{} of @water{600%ml} on to boil with the @chicken stock pot{1}. Stir to
dissolve your stock pot and once boiling add the @couscous{300%g} and a drizzle of
@olive oil{a drizzle} to the pot. Take the pot off the heat, put a lid on and leave
to the side for your couscous to absorb the stock.

While everything else is cooking, put a #frying pan{} on medium heat with a drizzle
of @oil{a drizzle} and lay in your pork. Leave the marinade liquid behind. Fry for
~{7-8%minutes} on each side.

> The pork should caramelise slightly but if it starts burning, turn the heat right
> down.

> The pork is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Once your pork has cooked add the marinade liquid to the pan and bubble away for
~{2%minutes}. Remove from the heat and put your pork on a #chopping board{} to rest
for a couple of mins.

Fluff up your couscous with a #fork{}, add your cooked veggies, caramelised onion and
half your parsley to the pot. Stir everything together. Slice your pork into roughly
1cm slices.

Serve your couscous in #bowls{} with your sliced pork on top and a good spoonful of
sauce. Sprinkle your remaining parsley on top. Enjoy!